The current produces when negative and positive electrodes of the cell are short circuited at a zero mV voltage. VOC (V) is the voltage across negative and positive electrodes under open circuit condition at zero milliampere (mA) current or simply, the potential difference between the conduction band energy of semiconducting material and the redox potential of electrolyte. Pmax is the maximum efficiency of the DSSC to convert sunlight into electricity. The ratio of maximum power output (Jmp × Vmp) to the product (VOC × JSC) gives FF.FF=AreaAAreaB=Jmp×VmpJSC×VOC\documentclass[12pt]{minimal}
